  <!-- WHAT IS A CP12 -->
  <section class="section-pad" style="background:var(--bg);">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>What Is a Gas Safety Certificate (CP12)?</h2>
      <p class="section-sub">Everything Liverpool landlords need to know about the CP12 in plain English.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1rem;margin-top:1.5rem;">
        <div style="background:var(--white);border:1px solid var(--border);border-top:3px solid var(--orange);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:1.75rem;text-align:center;">
          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);margin-bottom:0.75rem;">The Official Name</h3>
          <p style="color:var(--muted);">A Gas Safety Certificate is officially called a Landlord Gas Safety Record (LGSR) or CP12. It is an official document issued by a <a href="https://www.gassaferegister.co.uk" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Gas Safe registered engineer</a> confirming that all gas appliances, flues and pipework in a property have been inspected and are safe to use.</p>
        </div>
        <div style="background:var(--white);border:1px solid var(--border);border-top:3px solid var(--orange);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:1.75rem;text-align:center;">
          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);margin-bottom:0.75rem;">Who Needs One</h3>
          <p style="color:var(--muted);">Under the <a href="https://www.hse.gov.uk/gas/landlords/index.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Gas Safety (Installation and Use) Regulations 1998</a>, all landlords with gas appliances in their rental properties must have a valid CP12. It must be renewed every 12 months. Homeowners are not legally required to have one but are strongly advised to.</p>
        </div>
        <div style="background:var(--white);border:1px solid var(--border);border-top:3px solid var(--orange);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:1.75rem;text-align:center;">
          <h3 style="color:var(--navy);margin-bottom:0.75rem;">How Long It Is Valid</h3>
          <p style="color:var(--muted);">A CP12 is valid for 12 months from the date of issue. Landlords must keep a copy of the certificate for at least two years, provide a copy to existing tenants within 28 days of the check, and give new tenants a copy before they move in. See further guidance at <a href="https://www.citizensadvice.org.uk/housing/renting-privately/during-your-tenancy/gas-safety-checks/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Citizens Advice</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

